english:
  title: A Lament
  author: Sung Kan
  language: eng
  text: |-
    At dawn I ate my meager meal and climbed the eastern ridge,
    At dusk I returned to the desolate village and wept.
    My clothes are torn, my elbows bare to the wind,
    My jar stands empty—no grain stored within.
    My youngest child tugs at my rags and cries,
    'Father, when will we have rice and gruel again?'
    The magistrate's men came demanding taxes,
    And bound my aged wife with cruel rope.
    I fled over the wall to the towering heights,
    Hiding ten days among the thorns and brambles.
    Crouched in the grass, I crept through shadows,
    As the sun sank and the valley grew dark.
    Spirits whistled from the riverbank,
    And bitter winds shook through the forest.
    My soul trembled and nearly fled my body,
    Each step I took, I gasped three, four times for breath.
    Alas, these crooked clerks and their schemes!
    How swiftly they squeeze the blood from the poor!
    The magistrate himself may not be unkind,
    But you—your hearts are black as pitch.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The poem depicts the plight of a peasant under oppressive tax collection during the Joseon period, where local officials often exceeded their authority in extracting payments from the desperate poor.
  - key: ''
    value: '''Spirits'' (魑魅) refers to malevolent supernatural beings of traditional East Asian folklore, here representing the terror and despair of the speaker''s flight.'
  - key: ''
    value: The final couplet distinguishes between the nominal authority (the magistrate) and those who enact cruelty—a critique of bureaucratic corruption rather than the system itself.
